WEBVTT

00:02.103 --> 00:05.339
Previously on "The Rookie"...
I-I think I have a lead
on Rosalind.

00:05.373 --> 00:07.808
The forensic linguistics
are a match to Rosalind Dyer.

00:07.841 --> 00:09.243
Hello, John.

00:09.277 --> 00:11.545
Nolan: Coming back to L.A.
was a bad move.

00:11.579 --> 00:14.182
Nolan: This wasn't all you.
You had help.

00:14.215 --> 00:17.085
Another acolyte.
Harper: Exactly what kind of
sicko are we dealing with here?

00:17.118 --> 00:19.253
Laura: Killers like this,
they don't stop.

00:19.287 --> 00:21.722
We got a name out of Denver
Sanitation -- Jeffrey Boyle.

00:21.755 --> 00:23.991
Rosalind: He was very excited
when I pitched him the idea.

00:24.024 --> 00:24.992
He loved the artistry of it.

00:25.025 --> 00:27.195
Yes.
This is Officer John Nolan.

00:27.228 --> 00:28.696
I have Rosalind Dyer
in custody.

00:28.729 --> 00:31.031
[ Gunshot ]

00:31.065 --> 00:32.366
**

00:32.400 --> 00:34.102
Do you think she did this
on purpose?

00:34.135 --> 00:36.437
All that means is that we can
focus on catching her accomplice

00:36.470 --> 00:38.572
before he kills
anyone else.

00:38.606 --> 00:40.708
Here comes the feds to help.
[ Siren wailing ]

00:41.975 --> 00:43.844
[ Theme music plays ]

00:43.877 --> 00:46.514
Anchor: Serial killer
Rosalind Dyer is dead,

00:46.547 --> 00:49.783
fatally shot earlier today
by an unknown accomplice

00:49.817 --> 00:52.686
after she was apprehended
by the LAPD.

00:52.720 --> 00:55.189
We can confirm that
Rosalind Dyer was killed today

00:55.223 --> 00:58.526
by a sniper's bullet we believe
was fired by this man.

00:58.559 --> 01:00.594
Now, we do not know yet
his true identity,

01:00.628 --> 01:02.096
but he has been
operating locally

01:02.130 --> 01:05.032
under the alias Jeffrey Boyle.
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

01:05.065 --> 01:07.301
In addition to assisting
Rosalind Dyer in this morning's

01:07.335 --> 01:10.070
attempted murder
of firefighter Bailey Nune,

01:10.104 --> 01:12.940
we believe that Boyle
is responsible

01:12.973 --> 01:14.875
for at least three other,
unrelated murders.

01:14.908 --> 01:18.112
So we're asking anyone with
information to please call 911

01:18.146 --> 01:19.713
or the FBI tip line.

01:19.747 --> 01:23.050
But be mindful -- This is
an extremely dangerous man.

01:23.083 --> 01:27.721
**

01:27.755 --> 01:29.923
[ Sirens wailing,
police radio chatter ]

01:29.957 --> 01:31.725
[ Helicopter blades whirring ]

01:31.759 --> 01:34.094
I don't get it.

01:34.128 --> 01:36.397
Rosalind busted out of prison.

01:36.430 --> 01:38.065
She could be on a beach,

01:38.098 --> 01:40.734
having umbrella drinks
for the rest of her life.

01:40.768 --> 01:42.770
Instead,
she plans her own murder.

01:42.803 --> 01:45.306
It's fascinating, really --
you know, on a clinical level.

01:45.339 --> 01:47.575
The most extreme case
of a manipulative,

01:47.608 --> 01:49.777
narcissistic psychopath
I've ever seen,

01:49.810 --> 01:51.945
controlling everything
down to the way she died.

01:51.979 --> 01:54.748
Okay. So, what are the odds
our guy is both an evil genius

01:54.782 --> 01:56.517
and an expert sniper?

01:56.550 --> 01:58.652
Not out of the question,
but it is unlikely.

01:58.686 --> 02:01.455
I don't get a former-military
vibe off of him.

02:01.489 --> 02:05.259
You know, I played a sniper once
in a video-game adaptation.

02:05.293 --> 02:07.428
On a shot over 100 yards,
the math you have to do

02:07.461 --> 02:10.298
to calculate the windage
and elevation is a bitch.

02:10.331 --> 02:12.200
I would have shot
from over here.

02:12.233 --> 02:13.534
Why?

02:13.567 --> 02:14.935
Good cover.

02:14.968 --> 02:16.770
Close to the canyon gate.

02:16.804 --> 02:19.673
Pull the trigger
and you're gone.

02:21.475 --> 02:22.876
Simone:
What the hell?

02:22.910 --> 02:24.312
Carter:
What is it?

02:24.345 --> 02:26.680
W--
A tiny little mask.

02:26.714 --> 02:30.451
Like the ones doctors used to
wear during the bubonic plague.

02:30.484 --> 02:32.720
LAPD found one of those masks
in Boyle's workshop.

02:32.753 --> 02:33.954
What's with the beak?

02:33.987 --> 02:35.956
Laura: They filled it with herbs
to purify the air,

02:35.989 --> 02:38.226
prevent contagion --
like an early gas mask.

02:38.259 --> 02:39.560
So he left that here
for us to find.

02:39.593 --> 02:41.729
He wanted us to find it.
But w-why would he do that?

02:41.762 --> 02:43.631
Laura: The black death
decimated Europe.

02:43.664 --> 02:46.166
Almost half the population
perished.

02:46.200 --> 02:49.503
It's his way of telling us...
more death is coming.

02:49.537 --> 02:52.240
**

02:52.273 --> 02:57.245
**

02:57.278 --> 02:59.413
I know we had a deal, but --
Please.

02:59.447 --> 03:01.048
I don't need a lecture
right now.

03:01.081 --> 03:02.883
We need to catch this guy
before he kills somebody else.

03:02.916 --> 03:04.652
Evelyn, I'm sorry.

03:04.685 --> 03:06.186
I have to go.

03:06.220 --> 03:08.322
Everything all right?
Yes.

03:08.356 --> 03:09.823
Okay.
That's a lie.

03:09.857 --> 03:11.592
Carter, I need everyone
at their best for this one,

03:11.625 --> 03:13.060
so if there's something
going on --

03:13.093 --> 03:14.828
It's my day
to pick up my son.

03:14.862 --> 03:17.030
Evelyn and I are...

03:17.064 --> 03:19.199
I'm sorry, Carter.
Listen.

03:19.233 --> 03:22.236
I've been in your shoes --
divorced three times.

03:22.270 --> 03:25.373
So if you're wondering
what to do or how to feel

03:25.406 --> 03:28.942
or even the name
of a good divorce lawyer,

03:28.976 --> 03:31.445
you hit me up, huh?

03:31.479 --> 03:34.014
Thanks.
Good.

03:34.047 --> 03:36.684
Brendon: Hey.
So, uh, what's the plan, boss?

03:36.717 --> 03:38.919
Well, by now, Jeffrey Boyle
has changed his appearance

03:38.952 --> 03:40.588
and gone to ground,
so question is

03:40.621 --> 03:42.290
does he stay local
or hit the road?

03:42.323 --> 03:44.925
Given the Denver case
the LAPD found,

03:44.958 --> 03:46.727
I say he hits the road.

03:46.760 --> 03:48.061
I mean, he's a traveler
by nature.

03:48.095 --> 03:49.062
I agree.

03:49.096 --> 03:50.464
[ Gasps ]
Did you hear that?

03:50.498 --> 03:51.965
We should divide
and conquer.

03:51.999 --> 03:53.434
I'm interested
in the victim

03:53.467 --> 03:55.269
LAPD pulled out
of Boyle's practice trap.

03:55.303 --> 03:56.637
M.E. has her on the table
right now.

03:56.670 --> 03:57.871
Good.
Hit the morgue.

03:57.905 --> 03:59.540
We need to get an I.D.
on that woman fast,

03:59.573 --> 04:01.309
find out whether she was yanked
off the street

04:01.342 --> 04:02.743
or if this guy seduces
his victims.

04:02.776 --> 04:04.878
And if it's the latter,
then maybe he screwed up

04:04.912 --> 04:06.747
and left a clue behind
that we can follow.

04:06.780 --> 04:08.382
Now, Laura,
what do you want to do?

04:08.416 --> 04:10.217
A deep dive into the trap
he built for Bailey.

04:10.250 --> 04:12.786
I want to get a sense of his
skill level, his artistry.

04:12.820 --> 04:15.289
My instinct is that he defines
himself by the way he kills.

04:15.323 --> 04:16.790
That's how we're gonna
catch him.

04:16.824 --> 04:18.058
Great.
Do it.

04:18.091 --> 04:19.793
I'll call D.C.
and get additional resources.

04:19.827 --> 04:20.661
We're gonna need them.

04:20.694 --> 04:22.496
Can I drive?

04:22.530 --> 04:24.465
Of course not.

04:24.498 --> 04:26.266
You work a serial killer case
before?

04:26.300 --> 04:28.101
Worked three, solved two.

04:28.135 --> 04:29.303
The third?

04:29.337 --> 04:30.838
I'll tell you
about it sometime

04:30.871 --> 04:32.239
if you never want to sleep
again.

04:32.272 --> 04:34.775
Before we go in,
best prepare.

04:34.808 --> 04:37.645
[ Indistinct conversations,
machinery whirring ]

04:37.678 --> 04:39.580
[ Sniffs ]

04:39.613 --> 04:41.682
I've seen my share
of dead bodies.

04:41.715 --> 04:42.816
I'm good.

04:42.850 --> 04:44.352
How about the smell of one --
or several?

04:44.385 --> 04:46.320
You ever smelled the inside
of a locker room

04:46.354 --> 04:47.988
after football practice
on a hot day?

04:48.021 --> 04:49.122
Simone.

04:49.156 --> 04:50.290
[ Whispering ]
I'm good.

04:50.324 --> 04:52.159
[ Hinges squeaking ]

04:55.128 --> 04:57.431
Sweet Jesus,
take me now.

04:57.465 --> 04:59.166
Hey.

04:59.199 --> 05:01.602
Dr. Song,
we spoke on the phone.

05:01.635 --> 05:03.871
I'm Special Agent Hope.
This is Special Agent Clark.

05:03.904 --> 05:06.940
Yes. I just completed
our Jane Doe autopsy.

05:06.974 --> 05:09.410
[ Metal rattling ]

05:12.312 --> 05:14.648
Our vic was found
with water in her lungs

05:14.682 --> 05:17.518
and electrical burns
on her lower extremities.

05:17.551 --> 05:18.986
Were you able
to pull prints?

05:19.019 --> 05:20.621
No.
She was in the water too long.

05:20.654 --> 05:22.790
Her skin has lost
all elasticity.

05:22.823 --> 05:24.324
She basically fell apart
on my table.

05:24.358 --> 05:26.660
How is her face
still intact?

05:26.694 --> 05:29.463
Ah. Postmortem gas releasing
made her buoyant.

05:29.497 --> 05:30.898
She was floating face up.

05:33.200 --> 05:35.235
Hey, it's okay
if you need to step outside.

05:35.268 --> 05:38.872
No, no.
I'm staying right here.

05:38.906 --> 05:41.008
And I'm gonna be strong for her
so we can catch who did this.

05:43.777 --> 05:45.479
Is that a tattoo
on her neck?

05:45.513 --> 05:46.480
Yes.

05:46.514 --> 05:47.981
The heart could indicate
a loved one,

05:48.015 --> 05:51.552
but Q is not a common letter
for a name.

05:51.585 --> 05:55.989
Wait.
Queen of Hearts Car Club.

05:56.023 --> 05:59.026
That tattoo...
is their logo.

06:00.528 --> 06:03.196
Laura: I can't believe
you got Bailey out in time.

06:03.230 --> 06:04.832
Uh, technically,
we didn't.

06:04.865 --> 06:06.600
She was dead
when we pulled her out,

06:06.634 --> 06:08.201
but Chen saved her.
Hmm.

06:08.235 --> 06:10.571
What does the intricacy of this
indicate to you?

06:10.604 --> 06:13.607
Well, it must have taken weeks
to put together.

06:13.641 --> 06:15.909
I mean, he planned this
for a long time.
Yeah.

06:15.943 --> 06:18.846
Guy's organized,
not spontaneous.
[ Shutter clicking ]

06:18.879 --> 06:21.449
Enjoys the prelude,
sense of control,

06:21.482 --> 06:25.185
watching his victims come
face-to-face with their fate,

06:25.218 --> 06:28.255
feeling that dread
and anticipation.

06:30.223 --> 06:32.626
What?
Not a fan of profiling?

06:32.660 --> 06:34.394
No offense,
but in my experience

06:34.428 --> 06:36.930
the best way to catch a killer
is with evidence, witnesses,

06:36.964 --> 06:38.532
and good old fashioned
police work,

06:38.566 --> 06:41.602
not speculation on
what messed him up as a child.

06:41.635 --> 06:43.403
You're telling me
that you're not the man you are

06:43.437 --> 06:45.639
because of what happened to you
as a kid?

06:49.342 --> 06:51.211
Huh.
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

06:51.244 --> 06:52.946
Tim:
"Huh" what?

06:52.980 --> 06:55.816
Well, it's just fascinating.

06:55.849 --> 06:57.084
What is?

06:57.117 --> 06:58.552
The construction
on this trap

06:58.586 --> 07:01.088
shows exceptional
metalwork skill.

07:01.121 --> 07:04.492
But the welding pattern
here around the window

07:04.525 --> 07:05.759
has no functionality.

07:05.793 --> 07:07.628
It's completely decorative.

07:07.661 --> 07:09.897
Which means our subject
took pride in building this

07:09.930 --> 07:11.231
on a design level.

07:11.264 --> 07:14.234
So he enjoyed the making
almost as much as the killing.

07:14.267 --> 07:15.769
Exactly.

07:15.803 --> 07:18.772
We just need to figure out
how that helps us catch him.

07:18.806 --> 07:20.608
[ Siren wailing in distance ]

07:20.641 --> 07:22.810
I wish I could tell you
that you get used to it,

07:22.843 --> 07:24.845
but the bad ones...

07:24.878 --> 07:27.280
they'll always be there
when you close your eyes.

07:27.314 --> 07:28.949
I know.

07:28.982 --> 07:32.620
I lost a dozen kids
when I was a counselor.

07:32.653 --> 07:35.122
Drugs, homicides,
suicides.

07:35.155 --> 07:37.825
One of my girls
was abducted.

07:37.858 --> 07:39.693
Renata Sams.

07:39.727 --> 07:42.830
D.C. police had no leads,
so they barely worked the case.

07:42.863 --> 07:46.433
That baby didn't even get
a mention on the local news.

07:46.466 --> 07:49.136
Wrong skin tone
for prime time.

07:49.169 --> 07:53.306
Her remains were discovered
about two months later.

07:53.340 --> 07:54.341
That's it.

07:54.374 --> 07:56.844
I mean, the case
is still unsolved.

07:56.877 --> 07:58.979
The investigation
just ended.

07:59.012 --> 08:02.616
She's just a case file
in the damn basement.

08:02.650 --> 08:05.553
[ Cellphone chimes ]

08:05.586 --> 08:09.222
Okay.
We got a hit on our Jane Doe.

08:09.256 --> 08:11.559
Local chapter
of the Queen of Hearts Car Club

08:11.592 --> 08:14.361
identify her
as Sadie Frank.

08:14.394 --> 08:16.797
It's the nightmare
you always have.

08:16.830 --> 08:19.900
Sadie and I made a pact
when we moved in together.

08:19.933 --> 08:21.134
Two single girls in L.A.

08:21.168 --> 08:23.403
We always texted
if we were gonna be out late.

08:23.436 --> 08:27.708
So when I did hear from her,
I didn't...

08:27.741 --> 08:31.211
Simone:
Look, I know this is a lot.

08:31.244 --> 08:33.346
And my heart breaks
for you.

08:33.380 --> 08:35.883
But you need to be strong
for your girl right now.

08:37.184 --> 08:39.820
Have you ever seen this man
before?

08:39.853 --> 08:41.421
That's Jeff.

08:41.454 --> 08:44.057
Sadie met him
at the university library.

08:44.091 --> 08:45.492
He did this?

08:45.525 --> 08:47.227
Did she say anything
about him?

08:47.260 --> 08:50.063
Yeah.
Just that he was nice.

08:50.097 --> 08:52.532
Um, they both geeked out
over Gothic architecture.

08:52.566 --> 08:54.735
Sounds like she really liked
this guy.

08:54.768 --> 08:56.069
She did.

08:56.103 --> 08:58.171
So you met him.
Once.

08:58.205 --> 09:00.107
I mean,
he came over for dinner.
Really?

09:00.140 --> 09:02.042
Do you remember anything he said
or did that night?

09:02.075 --> 09:03.443
Did he say
where he lived?

09:03.476 --> 09:04.778
I was in my room studying.

09:04.812 --> 09:06.113
I only saw him
for like a minute.

09:07.447 --> 09:10.050
I just remember
how happy Sadie was

09:10.083 --> 09:12.052
because he had given her
some rare book

09:12.085 --> 09:13.587
on an artist that she liked.

09:13.621 --> 09:14.888
Did she keep the book?

09:14.922 --> 09:17.591
Uh, yeah.
It's on her night table.

09:18.626 --> 09:22.062
Based on what we know so far,
Jeffrey Boyle is precise,

09:22.095 --> 09:25.966
methodical, a planner who takes
pride in his creations.

09:25.999 --> 09:28.235
His M.O. has remained consistent
so far.

09:28.268 --> 09:30.738
All of his known victims
have died from drowning,

09:30.771 --> 09:33.774
which is a slow death
that he revels in.

09:33.807 --> 09:36.209
He relishes control,

09:36.243 --> 09:38.411
which is often a sign that our
subject feels he lacks control

09:38.445 --> 09:39.446
of his own life.

09:39.479 --> 09:41.815
Atlas:
Or he's just a show-off.

09:41.849 --> 09:44.284
I mean, this is a hell of a
complicated way to kill someone.

09:44.317 --> 09:47.655
Guy's arrogant. Ego-driven.
A grandstander.

09:50.691 --> 09:51.792
[ Whispering ]
Hi.

09:51.825 --> 09:53.226
[ Whispering ]
Hi. What are you doing here?

09:53.260 --> 09:56.630
D.C. sent me.
You didn't...know.

09:56.664 --> 09:58.732
[ Inaudible ]

09:58.766 --> 10:02.970
Uh, pardon the interruption.
Agent Stensen, please continue.

10:03.003 --> 10:04.672
Who is that?
Mark Atlas.

10:04.705 --> 10:07.474
Laura's partner before she got
kicked out of the BSU.

10:07.507 --> 10:08.341
Mm.

10:11.511 --> 10:14.447
An apparatus
this sophisticated --

10:14.481 --> 10:16.850
it's clear our subject
has been honing his skills

10:16.884 --> 10:18.919
since long before he met up
with Rosalind.

10:18.952 --> 10:20.854
But getting
an apprenticeship --

10:20.888 --> 10:23.957
that indicates someone who has
a strong desire for approval.

10:23.991 --> 10:26.193
Atlas: Or he linked up
with Rosalind

10:26.226 --> 10:27.360
to test himself
against the best.

10:27.394 --> 10:28.829
The ultimate way
to prove that --

10:28.862 --> 10:30.297
kill the queen
and take her crown.

10:30.330 --> 10:32.165
Or he was exorcising demons
from his past,

10:32.199 --> 10:34.167
craved acclaim from
a senior figure in his life.

10:34.201 --> 10:36.136
Not everyone was made into
a monster by someone.

10:36.169 --> 10:38.338
Not everyone was born
that way.

10:38.371 --> 10:40.974
[ Whispering ]
Either they're gonna fight or...

10:41.008 --> 10:44.712
If the best predictor of future
behavior is past behavior,

10:44.745 --> 10:48.315
then it's reasonable to assume
our subject will strike again.

10:48.348 --> 10:51.351
He's not a loner.
He craves a connection.

10:51.384 --> 10:53.153
He likes to show off.

10:53.186 --> 10:56.356
The ironwork he did on the trap
was ornamental.

10:56.389 --> 10:58.826
And the plague doctor mask
he left behind

10:58.859 --> 11:00.861
exhibits almost a sense
of whimsy.

11:00.894 --> 11:02.662
This indicates someone

11:02.696 --> 11:05.498
who doesn't just see his skills
as a means to an end

11:05.532 --> 11:09.369
but rather the ability
to express himself.

11:09.402 --> 11:12.205
[ Machinery whirring ]

11:17.711 --> 11:20.147
Um, if you're looking
for copper to steal,

11:20.180 --> 11:21.548
I saw some a ways back.

11:21.581 --> 11:22.750
Oh, no.

11:22.783 --> 11:24.684
I'm an artist,

11:24.718 --> 11:28.088
so I use the scrap as materials
for my sculpture.

11:29.923 --> 11:32.092
Like John Chamberlain?

11:32.125 --> 11:35.195
Or more figurative stuff,
like Stankiewicz?

11:35.228 --> 11:37.497
Um, I'm an artist, too.

11:37.530 --> 11:40.200
I like to think of my work
as more elemental.

11:40.233 --> 11:42.502
I love what the most primal
forces on earth --

11:42.535 --> 11:46.006
you know, heat, water, cold --
they do to things.

11:46.039 --> 11:48.708
How they change them,
test them,

11:48.742 --> 11:50.610
forge them
into something new.

11:52.112 --> 11:54.081
I'm sorry.
Am I being pretentious?

11:54.114 --> 11:56.449
Uh, a little.
[ Laughs ]

11:56.483 --> 12:02.222
Um, I'm, uh --
I'm Mia, by the way.

12:02.255 --> 12:05.292
Love that name.
I'm Owen.

12:05.325 --> 12:06.894
So, what kind of artist
are you?

12:06.927 --> 12:09.062
Oh.
Um, I draw.

12:09.096 --> 12:12.132
Mostly, um,
representational.

12:13.466 --> 12:15.135
Very nice.

12:15.168 --> 12:19.606
I guess we both search for truth
and the sublime in a disaster.

12:19.639 --> 12:21.708
Wow.
And I'm pretentious?

12:21.741 --> 12:24.544
[ Chuckles ]

12:24.577 --> 12:28.048
You know, there is a gnarly
semitruck wreck back that way

12:28.081 --> 12:30.117
if you want to
check it out.

12:32.419 --> 12:35.755
I thought
you'd never ask.

12:35.789 --> 12:37.390
Come on.

12:37.424 --> 12:40.293
[ Suspenseful music plays ]

12:45.966 --> 12:48.268
How can you
just waltz in here

12:48.301 --> 12:50.003
and contradict me like that
in front of everyone?

12:50.037 --> 12:51.972
I'm so sorry. I honestly thought
you knew I was coming.

12:52.005 --> 12:53.673
I'm still finding my footing
here.

12:53.706 --> 12:55.575
The last thing I need
is you undermining me.

12:55.608 --> 12:58.078
I would never undermine you.
I'm too scared of your mad face.

12:58.111 --> 12:59.779
See?
I do miss it, though.

12:59.813 --> 13:01.481
Yeah.
I'm sure you do.
Hey.

13:01.514 --> 13:03.516
Hey.

13:03.550 --> 13:06.619
You carried a box out of your
office and never looked back.

13:06.653 --> 13:08.588
Never returned
my phone calls.

13:08.621 --> 13:10.157
I'm sorry.

13:10.190 --> 13:14.527
I just needed a...clean break
after everything.

13:14.561 --> 13:15.929
Yeah.

13:15.963 --> 13:17.330
Heard you got promoted.

13:17.364 --> 13:18.932
I did.

13:18.966 --> 13:21.134
Hmm. Well, you know you only got
bumped up because I left.

13:21.168 --> 13:23.136
All right. Yeah.
Keep telling yourself that.

13:23.170 --> 13:25.538
You got a new partner?
Not yet.

13:25.572 --> 13:27.774
Everyone else suffers
in comparison.

13:27.807 --> 13:29.509
Garza:
So, the lab pulled prints

13:29.542 --> 13:31.811
off the book Simone and Carter
brought in.

13:31.845 --> 13:34.781
We finally have our subject's
real name -- Eli Reynolds.

13:34.814 --> 13:36.716
Born and raised outside
of Denver.

13:36.749 --> 13:39.486
So tell me, either of you, what
are the odds he went back home?

13:39.519 --> 13:40.520
After you.

13:40.553 --> 13:42.389
Oh, no. You first.
I insist.

13:42.422 --> 13:44.557
Why, thank you.
I'd say the odds are 50-50.

13:44.591 --> 13:47.360
But even if he's not there,
we'll gain crucial knowledge

13:47.394 --> 13:49.729
about his development
that will help us catch him.

13:49.762 --> 13:51.464
Good. Laura.
Laura: Yeah.

13:51.498 --> 13:53.133
What is that saying about
a stopped clock being right

13:53.166 --> 13:54.801
twice a day?
That's the spirit.

13:54.834 --> 13:57.704
Denver it is.
Wheels up in 30.

13:57.737 --> 13:59.439
[ Engines humming ]

14:01.074 --> 14:04.244
Eli Reynolds hasn't filed
a tax return in 10 years.

14:04.277 --> 14:06.346
He has zero
Internet presence.

14:06.379 --> 14:09.216
Well, he abandoned his old life,
but why?

14:09.249 --> 14:11.551
We need to figure out
what made him who he is today.

14:11.584 --> 14:13.987
Or...Or we recognize
that it's more likely

14:14.021 --> 14:15.923
our subject was born
with a brain

14:15.956 --> 14:18.358
predisposed to
narcissistic sociopathy.

14:18.391 --> 14:20.660
Ticking time bomb.
Waiting for his fuse
to be lit.

14:20.693 --> 14:22.395
Not every sociopath
is a murderer.

14:22.429 --> 14:23.931
Boom.

14:23.964 --> 14:26.333
Because a ton of kids
came through my office,

14:26.366 --> 14:28.668
and none of them turned out
serial killers.

14:28.701 --> 14:30.537
That you know of.
Atlas:
Answer me this, Simone.

14:30.570 --> 14:32.272
Were any of them sadists,
with antisocial

14:32.305 --> 14:33.773
or borderline
personality disorders?

14:33.806 --> 14:35.909
That's not the point,
Mark.
Sure it is, Laura.

14:35.943 --> 14:37.377
Every serial killer
has a different

14:37.410 --> 14:39.346
psychological diagnosis,
and nailing it down --

14:39.379 --> 14:41.248
Doesn't help us catch
our subject.

14:41.281 --> 14:42.515
You're wrong, as usual.

14:42.549 --> 14:45.018
Mm, no, I'm not.
Oh, really?

14:45.052 --> 14:47.020
Should we revisit
the Shallow Grave Killer --

14:47.054 --> 14:49.622
who I caught?
Okay. Enough.

14:49.656 --> 14:50.790
My goodness.

14:50.823 --> 14:53.593
The two of you,
you're like my sisters.

14:53.626 --> 14:56.696
And when we land,
Carter, Brendon, Atlas,

14:56.729 --> 14:58.631
you will pay Eli's father
a visit.

14:58.665 --> 15:00.133
Laura, you take Simone to do

15:00.167 --> 15:02.402
her "League of Extraordinary
Guidance Counselors" thing.

15:02.435 --> 15:04.104
We will look at
this man's childhood

15:04.137 --> 15:06.539
from two different angles,
okay?

15:06.573 --> 15:08.108
Works for me.

15:08.141 --> 15:09.642
May the best theory win.

15:09.676 --> 15:11.544
Oh, it will.

15:11.578 --> 15:14.547
**

15:14.581 --> 15:16.383
[ Dog barking in distance ]

15:16.416 --> 15:18.285
Yeah, it seems like
Laura's fitting in nicely

15:18.318 --> 15:20.287
at the L.A. field office.
Like a glove.

15:20.320 --> 15:21.955
How's L.A. treating her?
She settling in?

15:21.989 --> 15:23.390
She making friends?
She dating?

15:23.423 --> 15:25.392
Actually, she's, uh --
Go around back...

15:25.425 --> 15:27.060
Oh.
...in case he's inside
and tries to rabbit.

15:27.094 --> 15:28.528
Yeah. Sure.
[ Knock on door ]

15:32.932 --> 15:35.402
What?
Josh Reynolds?

15:35.435 --> 15:37.470
Yeah.
Who are you?

15:37.504 --> 15:40.073
Special Agent Hope, FBI.
This is Special Agent Atlas.

15:40.107 --> 15:41.674
We're here
about your son, Eli.

15:41.708 --> 15:43.310
Is he in the house?

15:43.343 --> 15:45.112
No.
Why?

15:45.145 --> 15:47.014
He's wanted
for multiple homicides.

15:47.047 --> 15:48.481
Invite us in.

15:50.817 --> 15:54.021
You mind if we take a look
around, confirm he's not here?

15:54.054 --> 15:55.588
You got a warrant?

15:55.622 --> 15:57.390
I can get one.

15:58.858 --> 15:59.892
Go ahead.

16:06.399 --> 16:08.968
You know, you're wrong
about Eli.

16:09.002 --> 16:11.871
The kid's not a killer.

16:11.904 --> 16:13.840
Have you spoken to your son
recently?

16:13.873 --> 16:16.109
Uh, months ago.
Just small talk.

16:16.143 --> 16:17.844
He was back East
somewhere.

16:17.877 --> 16:19.712
Back East where?

16:19.746 --> 16:21.114
I don't know.

16:21.148 --> 16:25.652
Look, he left home at 19.
We haven't talked much since.

16:25.685 --> 16:28.655
Why is that?
I'm his father,
not his best friend.

16:28.688 --> 16:31.058
Mr. Reynolds, these accusations
against your son are serious.

16:31.091 --> 16:33.460
If you know anything you're not
telling us, we need to know.

16:33.493 --> 16:37.297
I'd like to help you,
but...I can't.

16:37.330 --> 16:39.566
[ Bell rings ]
Martin: I remember Eli.

16:39.599 --> 16:42.469
He was, uh, troubled.

16:42.502 --> 16:45.472
Troubled how?
Oh, you know, the usual --

16:45.505 --> 16:48.475
problems at home,
acting out in school.

16:48.508 --> 16:51.211
Maybe...

16:51.244 --> 16:53.880
Maybe I could have done more
to help him back then.

16:53.913 --> 16:55.548
Look, I feel you.

16:55.582 --> 16:57.817
We only get these kids
for four years.

16:57.850 --> 17:00.087
I mean, there's only
so much you can do.

17:00.120 --> 17:03.756
What kind of problems
was Eli having at home?

17:03.790 --> 17:04.757
Abuse?

17:04.791 --> 17:06.826
Oh, I don't know.

17:06.859 --> 17:07.860
Maybe.

17:07.894 --> 17:09.696
Well, not maybe.

17:09.729 --> 17:11.264
It says you called
social services.

17:11.298 --> 17:13.900
Clearly you thought something
was going on.

17:13.933 --> 17:17.537
Well, there were signs
of malnourishment.

17:18.971 --> 17:21.841
I thought I saw some burns.

17:21.874 --> 17:25.512
Social services took a look,
and they didn't do anything.

17:25.545 --> 17:28.715
What did Eli say to you
about the abuse?

17:28.748 --> 17:31.518
Uh...not much.

17:31.551 --> 17:33.853
Mnh-mnh.
I take back what I said.

17:33.886 --> 17:35.422
You failed this kid,

17:35.455 --> 17:37.857
and now he's out there
torturing people to death.

17:37.890 --> 17:40.127
You will tell us
everything you know

17:40.160 --> 17:42.395
or I will make it
my mission

17:42.429 --> 17:45.332
to see that you are legally
charged for what you did.

17:46.599 --> 17:51.138
He told me his father
wanted to make him tougher...

17:51.171 --> 17:55.108
that he held him underwater
to test his endurance.

17:56.843 --> 17:58.445
[ Cellphone rings ]

17:58.478 --> 18:00.247
Hey.

18:00.280 --> 18:01.648
Simone: Are you still
at the dad's house?

18:01.681 --> 18:03.383
No. We just left.
Why?

18:03.416 --> 18:05.485
Eli's father abused him
as a child.

18:05.518 --> 18:07.620
He's re-creating
what he survived.

18:07.654 --> 18:10.390
We're going back.
The dad's lying.

18:10.423 --> 18:12.492
[ Engine revving,
tires screeching ]

18:12.525 --> 18:19.532
**

18:20.533 --> 18:22.235
Atlas:
Hey!

18:22.269 --> 18:24.237
Hey, hey, hey, hey.
Stop what you're doing.

18:24.271 --> 18:26.072
Put your hands up!
Hey! Stop!

18:26.105 --> 18:27.940
Atlas: Put your hands up!
Drop the box!

18:27.974 --> 18:30.843
Okay, okay, okay.
You guys are so serious.

18:32.679 --> 18:34.814
Hands behind your back.

18:34.847 --> 18:36.616
[ Handcuffs clicking ]

18:36.649 --> 18:39.118
**

18:44.023 --> 18:46.526
Carter: Burning evidence,
trying to destroy everything

18:46.559 --> 18:48.027
that could prove
your son's pathology --

18:48.060 --> 18:50.096
That screams accomplice.

18:50.129 --> 18:52.332
You're looking at life
without the possibility
of parole here.

18:52.365 --> 18:54.301
Eli left home at 19.

18:54.334 --> 18:57.036
I had jack-all
to do with it, okay?

18:57.069 --> 18:58.505
So why were you burning
his stuff?

18:58.538 --> 19:00.540
Because I knew you guys
would try to blame me.

19:00.573 --> 19:02.108
You're damn right.

19:02.141 --> 19:04.511
You abused your son.
You tortured him.

19:04.544 --> 19:07.380
Eli was born soft.

19:07.414 --> 19:10.517
I just tried to give him
strength and some backbone.

19:10.550 --> 19:12.785
Tried to make him
feel like a man.

19:12.819 --> 19:13.953
You made him into a killer.

19:13.986 --> 19:15.021
Where is he now?

19:15.054 --> 19:16.456
I told you.
I don't know.

19:16.489 --> 19:18.791
I don't believe you.
You need to tell us where he is.

19:18.825 --> 19:20.026
Man.

19:22.262 --> 19:25.365
I'm done talking.
I want a lawyer.

19:33.273 --> 19:35.408
It was great talking
to you guys.

19:35.442 --> 19:39.078
All right.
So he tested Eli's endurance.

19:39.111 --> 19:42.215
And then Eli follows,
tests his victims' endurance

19:42.249 --> 19:43.516
by putting them
in these boxes.

19:43.550 --> 19:48.255
But...what if torture
is like a twisted way

19:48.288 --> 19:49.656
to get to know
his victims?

19:49.689 --> 19:51.491
You know, he wants them to feel
the way he feels,

19:51.524 --> 19:54.827
suffer the way he suffers
so they understand him.

19:54.861 --> 19:56.729
Nobody wants to go through life
feeling alone.

19:56.763 --> 19:58.831
That's interesting.

19:58.865 --> 20:02.034
Denver forensics found
a pay-as-you-go phone

20:02.068 --> 20:04.271
at the bottom
of the barbecue.

20:04.304 --> 20:06.706
Oh.
It's a burner phone.

20:06.739 --> 20:08.341
Literally.

20:08.375 --> 20:09.376
Sorry.

20:09.409 --> 20:11.077
Given Eli's profile,
it makes sense

20:11.110 --> 20:12.945
he'd try to keep in contact
with his father,

20:12.979 --> 20:14.080
prove his worthiness.

20:14.113 --> 20:16.249
Garza: Yeah,
so if the lab can resurrect it,

20:16.283 --> 20:17.417
it might get us
Eli's location.

20:17.450 --> 20:19.051
You think he's in town?

20:19.085 --> 20:21.187
I think we need to wait
and see what this phone says.

20:21.220 --> 20:23.055
So we are all spending
the night -- the FBI way.

20:23.089 --> 20:25.392
Do I want to know
what the FBI way is?

20:25.425 --> 20:28.027
Two to a room.
In the cheapest motel
in town.

20:28.060 --> 20:29.629
We're bunkin' up.

20:29.662 --> 20:32.632
**

20:32.665 --> 20:34.567
* Everybody's talking,
everybody's talking *

20:34.601 --> 20:37.637
* They don't know a thing,
yeah *

20:37.670 --> 20:39.238
* Trying to walk the walk...

20:39.272 --> 20:42.074
Your theory
about the subject

20:42.108 --> 20:44.210
testing the endurance
of the victims was spot on.

20:44.243 --> 20:45.578
You study
behavioral psychology?

20:45.612 --> 20:47.414
[ Chuckles ]
Uh, no.

20:47.447 --> 20:48.981
No.
I was an actor.

20:49.015 --> 20:50.817
Really?
Really.

20:50.850 --> 20:52.719
Wow.
Yeah.

20:52.752 --> 20:54.987
I mean, you could -- you could
be Tom Cruise for all I know.

20:55.021 --> 20:56.155
I mostly watch baseball.

20:56.188 --> 20:59.058
No -- No offense.
No. None taken.

20:59.091 --> 21:00.993
I appreciate
the positive feedback.

21:01.027 --> 21:03.062
You know,
I-I don't get a lot here

21:03.095 --> 21:05.632
between being a rookie,
an ex-actor.

21:05.665 --> 21:08.435
Doesn't happen a lot.
So thank you.

21:08.468 --> 21:10.169
Make them respect
what you bring to the table.

21:10.202 --> 21:12.339
I mean, actors have to be
intuitive, right?

21:12.372 --> 21:14.006
Create backstories
to embody a character.

21:14.040 --> 21:15.642
That's basically
what good profilers do.

21:15.675 --> 21:17.910
So you're already ahead
of the game.

21:17.944 --> 21:20.680
Laura is a tough nut
to crack.

21:20.713 --> 21:23.350
Took me two months just to get
a-a laugh out of her.

21:23.383 --> 21:26.118
But, you know, when you let her
get to know your worth,

21:26.152 --> 21:29.456
she'll...still definitely be
super hard on you,

21:29.489 --> 21:31.123
but you'll have
her respect.

21:31.157 --> 21:33.125
Simone:
I raided the vending machine.

21:33.159 --> 21:35.862
What?
No Flaming Hot Cheetos?

21:35.895 --> 21:37.464
You don't need them,

21:37.497 --> 21:39.866
with all that heat
between you and Atlas.

21:39.899 --> 21:43.703
What? I-I don't know
what you're talking about.

21:46.005 --> 21:49.041
I've been around horny teenagers
for the last 20 years.

21:49.075 --> 21:51.744
My chemistry detector
is on point.

21:53.179 --> 21:56.315
You know, I also --
I vomit every time I see blood,

21:56.349 --> 21:59.285
s-so there's...
there's that, too.

21:59.318 --> 22:00.953
Laura says
it's an aversion reaction

22:00.987 --> 22:04.524
to being covered in stage blood
for so many years, but, uh...

22:04.557 --> 22:05.792
You ever tried B-MAC?

22:05.825 --> 22:07.460
The hamburger?

22:07.494 --> 22:10.062
Broad minded
affective coping.

22:10.096 --> 22:12.732
It's a way
to trick the brain.

22:12.765 --> 22:15.234
Think of something
that makes you happy.

22:15.267 --> 22:16.669
Quick. First thing
that comes to mind. Come on.

22:16.703 --> 22:19.406
Sink puppies.

22:19.439 --> 22:21.674
Dude, what?

22:21.708 --> 22:22.875
Sink puppies.

22:24.076 --> 22:26.646
When I was a kid,
I had a dog who had 10 puppies,

22:26.679 --> 22:30.049
and, uh, we wanted to get, like,
a really cute picture of them,

22:30.082 --> 22:31.217
so we --
we put them in the sink.

22:31.250 --> 22:32.885
And -- And I just remember
their, like,

22:32.919 --> 22:36.523
big eyes and the floppy ears
looking up at us.

22:36.556 --> 22:42.094
It's just a big bowl of, like...
fluffy...goodness.

22:42.128 --> 22:44.063
Sink puppies.

22:44.096 --> 22:45.432
Okay.

22:45.465 --> 22:47.834
So from now on,
when you see blood...

22:47.867 --> 22:49.936
Mm-hmm.
...think of sink puppies.

22:50.903 --> 22:53.339
We were great partners.

22:53.372 --> 22:56.409
And, you know,
there's a certain closeness

22:56.443 --> 22:58.077
that comes with that.

22:58.110 --> 23:00.780
Nothing more.
Simone: Come on.

23:00.813 --> 23:04.050
If girls can't have juicy talk
at a bedbug slumber party,

23:04.083 --> 23:07.019
it's gonna be
a boring night.

23:07.053 --> 23:09.789
Okay.
It's complicated.

23:09.822 --> 23:13.125
You know, when I left the BSU
and -- and went on sabbatical,

23:13.159 --> 23:17.897
he did reach out
and tried to be a friend.

23:17.930 --> 23:19.231
But I ghosted him.

23:19.265 --> 23:21.468
You know, and...

23:21.501 --> 23:24.103
I guess I just needed distance
from my old life.

23:24.136 --> 23:26.238
So...you slept with him.

23:26.272 --> 23:27.740
Got it.
You should've just said that.

23:27.774 --> 23:30.777
No, you don't got it.
We never hooked up.

23:30.810 --> 23:33.379
I was too busy being faithful
to my scumbag fiancÃ©

23:33.412 --> 23:35.247
to ever act on anything.

23:35.281 --> 23:38.317
Well, an ex is an ex
for a reason.

23:38.350 --> 23:41.353
Hey, you don't have a ring
on your finger, so...

23:43.856 --> 23:46.726
Finally took it off
yesterday.

23:46.759 --> 23:50.730
Funny how a little ring
could have such meaning, huh?

23:50.763 --> 23:53.933
I threw my last one
in the ocean.

23:53.966 --> 23:57.269
Well, emotionally
it felt great.

23:57.303 --> 24:00.339
Financially....
not so much.

24:00.372 --> 24:03.643
I haven't been single
in almost two decades.

24:03.676 --> 24:07.514
It feels like my world
is off its axis.

24:07.547 --> 24:09.916
They say your first divorce
is the hardest.

24:09.949 --> 24:11.918
Now, that is a lie.

24:11.951 --> 24:13.786
By the time you hear
three different women say

24:13.820 --> 24:15.522
that they made a mistake
by marrying you...

24:15.555 --> 24:17.123
[ Chuckles ]

24:17.156 --> 24:18.691
...you start thinking
maybe you're the problem.

24:18.725 --> 24:21.193
And that, my friend -- that is
when the real pain begins.

24:21.227 --> 24:23.796
So...
enjoy your first divorce.

24:23.830 --> 24:24.997
[ Clicks tongue ]

24:25.031 --> 24:27.199
[ Vehicles passing in distance ]

24:27.233 --> 24:28.935
Strange
but comforting advice.

24:28.968 --> 24:30.503
[ Exhales deeply ]

24:30.537 --> 24:35.842
The best way to get over someone
is to get under someone.

24:35.875 --> 24:38.044
We were ear-hustling.

24:38.077 --> 24:40.479
And this cute thing
across the pool is choosing.

24:40.513 --> 24:43.282
So you should go talk
to her.

24:43.315 --> 24:44.951
That's not gonna happen.

24:44.984 --> 24:47.286
You change your mind, Simone's
a pretty good wing woman.

24:47.319 --> 24:50.723
Although woman sitting alone
by a motel pool,

24:50.757 --> 24:51.724
it seems kind of sus.

24:51.758 --> 24:52.992
I'd pass.

24:53.025 --> 24:54.527
I'd hit that.

24:54.561 --> 24:56.028
Then be my guest.

24:56.062 --> 24:58.364
But last I checked, I didn't ask
for either of your opinions.

24:58.397 --> 25:00.166
I'm not even
officially divorced yet.

25:00.199 --> 25:02.034
I wouldn't even be ready
if I was.

25:02.068 --> 25:04.704
Besides, we're here
working a case.

25:04.737 --> 25:07.206
Hooking up with someone
is just...

25:07.239 --> 25:09.041
tacky.

25:09.075 --> 25:11.477
[ Knock on door,
siren wailing in distance ]

25:11.510 --> 25:15.314
* Howling quiet
like a wolf in the dark *

25:15.347 --> 25:17.984
**

25:18.017 --> 25:19.485
* I've been stung

25:19.518 --> 25:21.287
Um...

25:23.255 --> 25:26.859
...I was wrong
to cut you out of my life.

25:26.893 --> 25:29.596
Yes.
Yes, you were.

25:31.263 --> 25:33.332
I was just --
You know, I was...

25:33.365 --> 25:36.569
[ Sighs ]
...humiliated.

25:36.603 --> 25:38.237
And everyone thought
I was falling apart

25:38.270 --> 25:40.072
because Sam cheated
on me.

25:41.207 --> 25:43.075
But I think the worst part
was knowing

25:43.109 --> 25:48.047
that my best friend
in the unit, you...

25:48.080 --> 25:50.583
thought less of me.

25:52.451 --> 25:55.221
But you know
the good news?

25:56.723 --> 25:58.290
I think I'm back.

25:58.324 --> 25:59.358
Mm.

25:59.391 --> 26:00.526
Better than ever.
Wow.

26:00.559 --> 26:02.228
Yeah.

26:02.261 --> 26:04.463
How is it possible for
the second-best profiler I know

26:04.496 --> 26:06.799
to get even better?
Whoa. Second?

26:08.000 --> 26:10.102
Okay. Yeah.
The best.

26:12.672 --> 26:14.473
I'm really sorry.

26:16.175 --> 26:18.544
Please don't hate me.

26:18.577 --> 26:20.546
I could never hate you.
Come here.

26:20.579 --> 26:21.948
**

26:21.981 --> 26:27.987
* All this chemistry
has got me falling *

26:28.020 --> 26:29.922
**

26:29.956 --> 26:32.424
* Oh, me

26:32.458 --> 26:34.593
* Oh, my

26:34.627 --> 26:38.497
* I'm definitely high

26:38.530 --> 26:40.800
**

26:40.833 --> 26:43.469
* Good, good, good, good

26:43.502 --> 26:47.139
**

26:47.173 --> 26:50.242
* Good, good, good, good

26:50.276 --> 26:52.912
* Good, good

26:52.945 --> 26:58.184
**

26:58.217 --> 27:03.422
So, how does a cool
industrial art bro

27:03.455 --> 27:05.257
get into wine, anyway?

27:05.291 --> 27:07.026
Well...
[ Insects chirping ]

27:07.059 --> 27:08.460
...if you have good wine,

27:08.494 --> 27:11.597
it means you had grapes
that endured, right?

27:11.630 --> 27:14.533
The harsher the wind,
the rockier the soil,

27:14.566 --> 27:17.469
the more complex and interesting
the wine will be.

27:17.503 --> 27:19.271
Like your work.

27:19.305 --> 27:21.808
[ Chuckles ]
I'm noticing a theme here.

27:21.841 --> 27:23.710
[ Chuckles softly ]
You got me.

27:23.743 --> 27:26.813
[ Chuckles ]
And this is good wine.

27:26.846 --> 27:29.215
Uh, sorry.
[ Chuckles ]

27:29.248 --> 27:32.351
Um, it's just
most of my previous experiences

27:32.384 --> 27:34.020
came out of a box.

27:34.053 --> 27:35.988
Yeah, it's --
it's pretty good.

27:36.022 --> 27:38.324
Mm.
[ Gasps ]
But you know what?

27:38.357 --> 27:42.962
I've got a really, really
special bottle in the cellar.

27:42.995 --> 27:45.832
Come check it out.
[ Down-tempo music plays ]

27:45.865 --> 27:49.335
Um...m--
[ Chuckles softly ]

27:49.368 --> 27:52.371
Actually, um...
maybe next time.

27:52.404 --> 27:57.043
I, um...
I just had so much already.

27:57.076 --> 28:00.112
Sure?
Trust me, you're gonna love it.

28:01.113 --> 28:03.049
Uh, no.

28:03.082 --> 28:05.752
Um, I should --
I should really --

28:05.785 --> 28:07.854
I think I should go.
I should head out.

28:08.788 --> 28:10.389
Okay.
Yeah.

28:10.422 --> 28:16.863
**

28:16.896 --> 28:18.831
[ Doorknob rattling ]

28:18.865 --> 28:24.103
**

28:24.136 --> 28:29.408
**

28:29.441 --> 28:30.910
[ Doorknob rattling ]

28:30.943 --> 28:34.580
**

28:34.613 --> 28:36.482
[ Gasps ]

28:41.754 --> 28:44.623
[ Birds chirping,
vehicles passing ]

28:47.894 --> 28:50.462
You got in late
last night.

28:50.496 --> 28:53.699
I hope that smile means
it was as good as you imagined.

28:53.732 --> 28:56.402
Hm.
Better.

28:56.435 --> 28:57.804
Ooh!

28:57.837 --> 28:59.238
I know that's right!
Okay.

28:59.271 --> 29:02.875
That just stays between us,
or else.

29:02.909 --> 29:05.711
Snitches get stitches.

29:05.744 --> 29:07.446
You all right?

29:07.479 --> 29:09.215
You seemed a little down
when I walked up.

29:09.248 --> 29:11.383
I'm fine.

29:11.417 --> 29:12.718
No, you're not.

29:12.751 --> 29:13.986
Excuse me?

29:14.020 --> 29:15.988
You never want to show weakness
of any kind.

29:16.022 --> 29:18.057
You need people to think
you're competent,

29:18.090 --> 29:19.625
so you mask
your true feelings.

29:19.658 --> 29:22.061
Hold on.
Did you just profile me?

29:22.094 --> 29:23.729
Yeah.
It's kind of my thing.

29:23.762 --> 29:25.297
It's kind of annoying.

29:25.331 --> 29:26.765
But I'm right.

29:30.602 --> 29:34.440
I have been preparing
for this job my whole life.

29:34.473 --> 29:38.144
And I thought I was ready...
until this case.

29:38.177 --> 29:41.447
Every time
I close my eyes,

29:41.480 --> 29:44.283
I picture the victims and how
frightened they must have been,

29:44.316 --> 29:46.819
knowing how they
were gonna die.

29:46.853 --> 29:49.421
I figured by joining
the FBI,

29:49.455 --> 29:52.124
I would -- I would --
I would make a difference.

29:52.158 --> 29:53.625
I would --
I would be able to help.

29:53.659 --> 29:57.096
I would be there for people
who no one else was there for.

29:57.129 --> 29:58.797
Yeah.
That is what we're doing.

29:58.831 --> 30:01.667
So how do we...

30:01.700 --> 30:04.370
How do you live
with all this darkness?

30:04.403 --> 30:08.807
By reminding yourself that
there's more good than evil.

30:10.409 --> 30:13.512
But to be honest, sometimes
it feels like I'm just lying.

30:13.545 --> 30:15.347
Well...

30:15.381 --> 30:17.149
Mm.

30:17.183 --> 30:18.817
Atlas:
Hey, ladies.

30:18.851 --> 30:19.785
Simone:
Hey.

30:19.818 --> 30:21.487
Morning.

30:21.520 --> 30:23.822
Garza:
Oh, good. You're all here.

30:23.856 --> 30:28.527
Denver PD was able to recover
the data on the burnt phone.

30:28.560 --> 30:30.997
The dad only ever called
one number,

30:31.030 --> 30:32.498
and it was a burner phone
in Tucson.

30:32.531 --> 30:35.034
So we are headed to Arizona.

30:35.067 --> 30:36.668
Brendon: Our subject's phone
usually pings

30:36.702 --> 30:39.405
off one of these four towers.

30:39.438 --> 30:41.040
That's too wide
a search radius.

30:41.073 --> 30:43.375
We're gonna need more leads
in order to find this guy.

30:43.409 --> 30:45.311
We should look for
building-supply stores,

30:45.344 --> 30:47.046
places where he could store
specialty items

30:47.079 --> 30:48.547
to build
his torture chamber.

30:48.580 --> 30:49.882
We should also check
salvage yards.

30:49.916 --> 30:51.683
He uses scrap metal
for his art.

30:51.717 --> 30:53.485
Yeah.
That's good thinking.
Carter:
I already checked.

30:53.519 --> 30:55.321
Sales clerk at a scrapyard
thinks she saw our guy

30:55.354 --> 30:57.556
yesterday,
but his hair is different.

30:57.589 --> 30:58.925
Shorter.
Darker.

30:58.958 --> 31:00.426
Well, did he buy anything?

31:00.459 --> 31:03.195
'Cause if -- if he used
a credit card or a payment app,

31:03.229 --> 31:06.498
we can use that to find
his new identity or an address.

31:06.532 --> 31:07.833
No such luck.
He used cash.

31:07.866 --> 31:09.268
But it gets worse.

31:09.301 --> 31:12.438
He has another victim?
Looks like it.

31:12.471 --> 31:14.106
He was flirting
with a woman there --

31:14.140 --> 31:15.841
an art student at U of A.

31:15.874 --> 31:18.377
She left with him.
She's now reported missing.

31:18.410 --> 31:21.080
[ Breathing heavily ]
Let me out!

31:21.113 --> 31:23.582
[ Sobs ]

31:23.615 --> 31:25.952
Please.

31:25.985 --> 31:28.587
I'm dying.

31:28.620 --> 31:30.389
[ Metal creaking, clanks ]

31:30.422 --> 31:32.724
Eli:
We're all dying.

31:32.758 --> 31:34.293
You're suffering.

31:34.326 --> 31:37.696
**

31:37.729 --> 31:40.032
[ Gasps ]

31:40.066 --> 31:43.069
[ Sizzling ]
Easy. Easy.

31:43.102 --> 31:45.972
Steam will burn you faster
than dry heat.

31:46.005 --> 31:48.607
So pace yourself.

31:48.640 --> 31:49.976
This is gonna take
a while.

31:51.577 --> 31:53.812
Why are you doing this?

31:53.845 --> 31:55.481
Earth, plastic --

31:55.514 --> 31:57.649
When you expose them
to the elements,

31:57.683 --> 32:00.286
they're all
very predictable.

32:00.319 --> 32:03.655
But you, Mia...

32:03.689 --> 32:06.292
you're special.

32:06.325 --> 32:09.928
And I want to see
how this heat changes you

32:09.962 --> 32:14.900
and who or...
what you become.

32:14.933 --> 32:17.236
So please...
No.

32:17.269 --> 32:19.071
...tell me
how you're feeling.

32:19.105 --> 32:21.007
Take your time.

32:21.040 --> 32:22.674
[ Sobs ]

32:27.146 --> 32:30.016
Garza: Tucson P.D. got ahold
of the security-cam footage

32:30.049 --> 32:31.450
from the salvage yard.

32:31.483 --> 32:34.686
Reynolds was driving
a late-model silver Taurus

32:34.720 --> 32:36.455
with California plates.

32:36.488 --> 32:37.756
Please tell me
there's a local address

32:37.789 --> 32:39.091
attached to
the registration.

32:39.125 --> 32:42.761
It's a no-go. Cold plate.
Invalid number.

32:42.794 --> 32:45.297
Of course. So how the hell are
we supposed to find this guy?

32:45.331 --> 32:46.665
We do know
that his burner phone

32:46.698 --> 32:48.500
has only been used
southeast of Tucson.

32:48.534 --> 32:51.103
We know he'd seek privacy.
And metal fabrication is loud.

32:51.137 --> 32:52.704
He wouldn't want neighbors
close by.

32:52.738 --> 32:54.473
So we look for
outlying properties.

32:54.506 --> 32:56.475
Simone:
Wait. There is a town nearby.

32:56.508 --> 32:58.310
A small place
called Three Points.

32:58.344 --> 32:59.711
Kind of off the grid.

32:59.745 --> 33:01.713
Look for any recent
rental properties or --

33:01.747 --> 33:04.450
or anything under a business
name to hide his true identity.

33:04.483 --> 33:06.185
Wait, wait, wait.
I might have found something.

33:06.218 --> 33:08.354
Uh, 47 Sasabe Road.

33:08.387 --> 33:11.690
Rented two months ago.
It's isolated, quiet.

33:11.723 --> 33:14.193
Here.
Make a right, right here!

33:14.226 --> 33:17.029
[ Engines revving,
tires screeching ]

33:17.063 --> 33:24.070
**

33:24.503 --> 33:31.510
**

33:31.910 --> 33:33.712
[ Birds chirping ]

33:36.248 --> 33:37.649
That's his car.

33:37.683 --> 33:38.817
Judge approved
the arrest warrant.

33:38.850 --> 33:40.119
We're good to enter.

33:41.853 --> 33:44.323
Carter, Brendon, Atlas,
you guys go around back.

33:44.356 --> 33:46.192
Laura and Simone,
we take the front.

33:46.225 --> 33:47.726
Remember, this guy blew up
his own workshop in L.A.

33:47.759 --> 33:50.362
We have to assume he's got this
place booby-trapped as well.

33:50.396 --> 33:52.098
[ Metal creaking, clanks ]
[ Wheezing ]

33:52.131 --> 33:55.234
Eli: Stay with me.
Stay with me, Mia.

33:55.267 --> 33:57.703
What's going through
your head?

33:57.736 --> 33:59.105
Do you have any regrets?

34:00.439 --> 34:02.941
Yeah.

34:02.974 --> 34:05.043
I regret...

34:05.077 --> 34:08.247
meeting you,
you psycho!

34:08.280 --> 34:10.716
That's just mean.

34:10.749 --> 34:13.285
[ Cellphone beeping ]

34:13.319 --> 34:20.326
**

34:20.826 --> 34:23.028
I wish we had more time.

34:23.061 --> 34:24.563
[ Metal creaking, clanks ]

34:24.596 --> 34:26.765
Help me!

34:26.798 --> 34:28.300
Help!

34:28.334 --> 34:29.868
Help!

34:29.901 --> 34:32.138
[ Birds chirping ]

34:36.175 --> 34:37.609
That's not creepy at all.

34:40.446 --> 34:42.481
[ Whispering ]
Go, go, go. I got you.

34:42.514 --> 34:44.250
[ Hinges creaking ]

34:44.283 --> 34:45.384
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa!

34:45.417 --> 34:47.419
[ Explosion ]

34:47.453 --> 34:49.955
[ Both grunting, coughing ]

34:49.988 --> 34:52.291
FBI!

34:52.324 --> 34:54.193
Simone, back.

34:55.261 --> 34:57.363
Laura, stairs.

34:58.930 --> 35:00.466
Carter:
Agent down.

35:00.499 --> 35:02.668
Requesting backup
and an ambulance.

35:02.701 --> 35:04.570
Are you good to triage him?
Yeah.

35:04.603 --> 35:06.638
I need to back up the others.
Yeah, yeah. No, I got him.

35:06.672 --> 35:13.679
**

35:14.446 --> 35:16.282
[ Groans ]

35:16.315 --> 35:18.184
[ Breathing heavily ]
Oh, my God.

35:18.217 --> 35:21.453
Oh, my God.
Sink puppies.

35:21.487 --> 35:22.954
Sink puppies, sink puppies,
sink puppies,

35:22.988 --> 35:24.356
sink puppies,
sink puppies.

35:24.390 --> 35:26.024
[ Exhales deeply ]

35:26.057 --> 35:27.125
Oh, my God.
It worked.

35:27.159 --> 35:29.528
That's great.
How's it look?

35:29.561 --> 35:31.863
It's pretty gnarly,
but...it didn't get the artery.

35:31.897 --> 35:33.932
Here. I got you.
Let's get it elevated, okay?

35:33.965 --> 35:34.766
Yeah.
[ Grunts ]

35:34.800 --> 35:41.807
**

35:41.907 --> 35:48.914
**

35:49.014 --> 35:51.183
[ Crackling ]

35:51.217 --> 35:53.619
Mia:
[ Grunting, whimpering ]

35:53.652 --> 35:59.458
**

35:59.491 --> 36:05.897
**

36:05.931 --> 36:07.633
Simone:
Oh, my God.

36:07.666 --> 36:09.701
I found her.
She's downstairs.

36:09.735 --> 36:11.737
[ Metal creaking, clanks ]
[ Wheezing ]

36:11.770 --> 36:14.406
**

36:14.440 --> 36:17.175
[ Switch clicks ]
It's gonna be okay.

36:17.209 --> 36:18.544
Simone?

36:18.577 --> 36:20.712
**

36:20.746 --> 36:22.881
Go, go, go.
Simone, I got her.

36:22.914 --> 36:25.984
Mia:
[ Sobbing ]

36:26.017 --> 36:26.985
Oh, my God.

36:27.018 --> 36:28.587
It's okay.

36:28.620 --> 36:30.556
You're okay.

36:30.589 --> 36:32.258
You're okay.
Shh, shh, shh, shh.

36:32.291 --> 36:34.092
You're gonna be okay.

36:34.125 --> 36:35.361
[ Birds chirping ]

36:35.394 --> 36:37.396
Simone:
He's running!

36:37.429 --> 36:39.731
Go. Go with her.
Go with Simone.

36:39.765 --> 36:43.034
**

36:43.068 --> 36:45.671
[ Birds chirping ]

36:45.704 --> 36:52.444
**

36:52.478 --> 36:59.485
**

36:59.585 --> 37:06.592
**

37:09.495 --> 37:11.730
[ Screams, grunts ]

37:13.832 --> 37:15.401
[ Gunshots ]

37:15.434 --> 37:17.269
[ Grunts ]

37:17.303 --> 37:19.705
[ Breathing heavily ]

37:19.738 --> 37:22.641
Eli:
[ Groaning ]

37:22.674 --> 37:25.644
[ Handcuffs rattling, clicking ]

37:25.677 --> 37:27.379
You okay?

37:27.413 --> 37:30.749
Hell, no.
This is terrifying.

37:30.782 --> 37:34.686
**

37:39.157 --> 37:41.393
Garza: We just heard
from Victim Assistance.

37:41.427 --> 37:43.094
Mia's being released
from the hospital.

37:43.128 --> 37:44.396
She's gonna be okay.

37:44.430 --> 37:45.597
Simone:
Physically.

37:45.631 --> 37:47.966
But that poor girl
is gonna carry that trauma

37:47.999 --> 37:49.167
for the rest
of her life.

37:49.200 --> 37:50.936
Yeah, but thanks to everyone's
hard work today,

37:50.969 --> 37:52.304
she still has a life.

37:52.338 --> 37:54.640
True.
Also, forensics finished
going through the house.

37:54.673 --> 37:57.643
Found a box
of digital memory cards.

37:57.676 --> 38:00.446
He filmed every murder.
There were 12 victims total.

38:00.479 --> 38:02.113
Well, what we learned
about his childhood trauma

38:02.147 --> 38:03.281
tracked perfectly.

38:03.315 --> 38:05.784
He re-created the conditions
of his own abuse

38:05.817 --> 38:07.118
to kill his victims.

38:07.152 --> 38:09.254
And in his mind,
he survived what they couldn't.

38:09.287 --> 38:11.089
That's what I said
yesterday.

38:11.122 --> 38:13.592
Which supports the idea
that he's ego-driven,

38:13.625 --> 38:15.961
needing to feel in control of
and superior to his victims.

38:15.994 --> 38:17.463
Hmm?
Who he seduced

38:17.496 --> 38:20.298
by forging a connection
that he lost with his mother

38:20.332 --> 38:22.801
when she died and that he never
had with his abusive father.

38:22.834 --> 38:23.869
So I guess
we're both right.

38:23.902 --> 38:25.371
Well, I think
I'm mo right.

38:25.404 --> 38:28.607
I was right, too.
Of course you were, boo.

38:28.640 --> 38:30.609
[ Bell chimes ]
* I'm listening
to broken records *

38:30.642 --> 38:32.478
* Playing all the old hits

38:32.511 --> 38:35.381
So, how long did it take you
to go out on a date again?

38:35.414 --> 38:37.115
After which divorce?

38:37.148 --> 38:39.050
The hardest one.
Three years.

38:39.084 --> 38:40.886
No.

38:40.919 --> 38:43.221
I was terrified of getting hurt,
so I threw myself into the job.

38:43.254 --> 38:44.890
I'm not afraid of dating.
I'm --

38:44.923 --> 38:46.324
Okay.
Maybe a little.

38:46.358 --> 38:48.059
I'm just more afraid
of being disappointed.

38:48.093 --> 38:50.529
Evelyn was perfect,
and look how that turned out.

38:50.562 --> 38:54.400
Feels like finding a new perfect
is gonna be...impossible.

38:54.433 --> 38:55.734
Hey.

38:55.767 --> 38:58.404
Could be tomorrow,
could be three years from now.

38:58.437 --> 39:00.171
Only you'll know
when you're ready.

39:00.205 --> 39:02.207
Now, in the meantime,
I'm gonna buy you a drink,

39:02.240 --> 39:04.209
and then we're gonna find you
a new place to live.

39:04.242 --> 39:06.545
Nice little bachelor pad,
huh?

39:06.578 --> 39:08.680
'Cause that SRO is --
It's gruesome.

39:09.948 --> 39:12.217
It's gruesome.
Yeah.

39:12.250 --> 39:13.719
[ Exhales deeply ]
Phew.

39:13.752 --> 39:14.820
[ Bell chimes ]

39:14.853 --> 39:17.523
Simone: Hey.
Hi.

39:17.556 --> 39:20.358
Thanks for having my back
out there today.

39:20.392 --> 39:22.894
Yeah.
Mm. This one was tough.

39:22.928 --> 39:24.362
Mm.

39:24.396 --> 39:26.064
Can I give you
some more advice?

39:26.097 --> 39:28.867
I'm listening.

39:28.900 --> 39:31.703
We often come face-to-face
with evil here,

39:31.737 --> 39:34.773
and we don't always come out
on top.

39:34.806 --> 39:38.544
So find your own good
somewhere away from this job

39:38.577 --> 39:41.046
and just cling on to it
with all you've got.

39:43.214 --> 39:45.884
You do it, too, you know.
Mask your feelings.

39:45.917 --> 39:48.286
I mean, you were right about me.
I do it sometimes.

39:48.319 --> 39:50.422
But, girl,
you do it all the time.

39:50.456 --> 39:52.558
I respectfully disagree.

39:52.591 --> 39:54.760
Okay.
Well, what about Atlas?

39:54.793 --> 39:57.095
What about him?

39:57.128 --> 40:00.298
It -- It was a one-time thing,
and...

40:00.331 --> 40:02.768
I don't want to, uh,
complicate our friendship.

40:02.801 --> 40:04.636
Mm-kay.

40:04.670 --> 40:08.440
I do like what you said, though,
about finding your own good.

40:08.474 --> 40:11.577
There is, um,
this woman I've been seeing --

40:11.610 --> 40:13.111
Dina.

40:13.144 --> 40:15.581
I'm going to find her.
Mm.

40:15.614 --> 40:19.818
And, um,
you do give solid advice,

40:19.851 --> 40:22.754
but you should also take
some of it.

40:22.788 --> 40:25.791
Because you deserve
to find your own good too.

40:25.824 --> 40:30.762
**

40:30.796 --> 40:31.930
Brendon:
Oh, my God.

40:31.963 --> 40:33.665
My -- My blood phobia
is gone.

40:33.699 --> 40:35.066
I can look at anything now.

40:35.100 --> 40:36.267
Thank you, sink puppies.

40:36.301 --> 40:38.403
God. You just get weirder
and weirder.

40:38.436 --> 40:39.838
Hey, it was a pleasure
working with you.

40:39.871 --> 40:41.006
You got my number.
Don't be a stranger.

40:41.039 --> 40:42.073
All right.
See you, buddy.

40:42.107 --> 40:43.141
Take it easy.
Yep.

40:45.276 --> 40:46.912
I know why you're
hard on him,

40:46.945 --> 40:49.648
but he could make
a hell of a profiler one day.

40:49.681 --> 40:51.182
I agree.

40:51.216 --> 40:53.919
But don't you dare tell him
I said that.

40:53.952 --> 40:55.787
He has a big enough ego
as it is.

40:55.821 --> 40:57.856
[ Chuckles softly ]

40:57.889 --> 41:00.492
I'm glad D.C. sent you.

41:00.526 --> 41:02.494
We always work well
together.
Mm.

41:02.528 --> 41:08.266
And it was, um, nice,
you know, to, uh...

41:08.299 --> 41:09.367
catch up.

41:09.400 --> 41:12.638
Yeah. Catching up
was my favorite part.

41:12.671 --> 41:14.706
[ Chuckles ]
And, uh...

41:14.740 --> 41:17.375
I want to make it clear
that I'd really like

41:17.408 --> 41:20.912
whatever this thing is
between us to go somewhere.

41:22.213 --> 41:25.216
But I know
that isn't gonna happen.

41:25.250 --> 41:28.720
I hope you know
how much you mean to me,

41:28.754 --> 41:30.722
how much I'd love
to say yes.

41:30.756 --> 41:33.992
But I just -- I lost myself
in my last relationship.

41:35.260 --> 41:38.730
And this move to L.A.,
this unit...

41:38.764 --> 41:40.866
it's about me finding myself
again.

41:40.899 --> 41:41.867
Mm.

41:41.900 --> 41:44.035
Alone.

41:45.170 --> 41:46.104
For now.

41:47.739 --> 41:52.544
But it doesn't mean
we can't keep catching up...

41:52.578 --> 41:53.879
maybe,
before you leave.

41:53.912 --> 41:54.880
Oh.

41:54.913 --> 41:56.715
* Oh, oh, oh, oh

41:56.748 --> 42:00.518
* Alone tonight

